    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "based on twitter interactions @mwaskom is :+1: on this functionality, as are a few others. As Thomas mentioned, there isn't a clean way for us to do this only in the kernel. Moreover, this isn't the functionality that PDB has out of the box, so the fact that Ctrl-C didn't pop you out of ipdb was an IPython invention.\n\n``` python\nPython 2.7.6 (default, Mar 22 2014, 15:40:47)\n[GCC 4.8.2] on linux2\nType \"help\", \"copyright\", \"credits\" or \"license\" for more information.\n>>> import pdb\n>>> pdb.set_trace()\n--Return--\n> <stdin>(1)<module>()->None\n(Pdb) print \"hello\"\nhello\n(Pdb) Traceback (most recent call last):\n  File \"<stdin>\", line 1, in <module>\n  File \"/usr/lib/python2.7/bdb.py\", line 53, in trace_dispatch\n    return self.dispatch_return(frame, arg)\n  File \"/usr/lib/python2.7/bdb.py\", line 88, in dispatch_return\n    self.user_return(frame, arg)\n  File \"/usr/lib/python2.7/pdb.py\", line 190, in user_return\n    self.interaction(frame, None)\n  File \"/usr/lib/python2.7/pdb.py\", line 210, in interaction\n    self.cmdloop()\n  File \"/usr/lib/python2.7/cmd.py\", line 130, in cmdloop\n    line = raw_input(self.prompt)\nKeyboardInterrupt\n>>> \"we're back in Python\"\n\"we're back in Python\"\n```\n"
  },
